Observations: These were moments where I was the most confident about the notes that I was playing and the positions that I needed to use, so I was most absorbed in the music itself and thinking more about the shape of the melody and the emotion of the piece.

Piece: 3rd Movement of Bach's Sonata in G Minor
Observations: They are the moments in the piece that I feel most confident playing. They often include changes in dynamics, and they also have some of the more complicated sections which I have worked hard to perfect in the past.
Comments: The performance is of a piece which I have played lots before, although I feel slightly out of practice (and out of breath!) so it is not the most comfortable I have been whilst playing it.
PerformanceFrequency: I play in public for an audience roughly once a month if it were to average out across the year, although I perform in front of others at rehearsals for roughly 7 hours per week.
ReadMusic: Yes I do read music, but I very rarely learn music by heart - only if I am explicitly told or expected to by someone in charge of a performance.

Measure numbers: Movement III: mm. 1-27, Movement IV: mm. 1-74
Observations: The moments at which I stopped being consciously aware of my performance were typically those at which I was most focused. This focus was lost when I made an error, or when a particular phrase was not played exactly how I intended it to sound. It was evident in the video that I lost focus and became consciously aware of my performance at these points because my movements became more deliberate and my phrasing was less fluid.
Comments: These pieces were certainly not stretching my technical ability. However, they were still challenging in their own ways as they made me focus far more on phrasing and articulation than I would while playing a study or a more technically challenging piece.
ReadMusic: I do read music in five-line Western Classical notation. I occasionally learn music off by heart, but when I do it is not intentional.

Observations:
generally they were the less technically difficult moments - any moments where I made a slip up or mistake would have taken me out of the moment, and I would have probably been distracted by making sure it didn't happen again until the next phrase.
also, in bars 43-44 because the notes are longer I would have been less absorbed in what I was doing and more likely to have my mind wander.
ReadMusic: Yes, and yes.

Observations: We collaboratively wrote this piece for a music and dementia programme so the moments that i became absorbed in the music, i associated with previous memories. I remember the happy and joyful feeling of playing this music with friends so I enjoy several parts of this piece.
ReadMusic: yes I read music, and it depends on the context of the performance. For example, I learn all my music by memory in the funk band that I am in, but I wouldn't learn my wind orchestra parts off by heart. It can vary with solo performance, depending on if I have to do a public performance (i prefer to not be 'glued' to the stand)

Observations:
1 - had settled into the piece, enjoying playing it, over initial nerves and feeling of 'ooh how am I going to sound today'
2 - main melody has come back again, but this time the second half is different so I was more focused on this new material, as well as my breathing as it was getting louder and so needed more support (but I'm a bit out of practice so wasn't playing as long phrases as usual) - powering through
3- difficult bit over for now, and a small motif, but very fun and satisfying to play so was just thinking about that and how it should sound (not the performance itself)
4 - again a fun bit to play, really like how it sounds, as it got towards end of phrase though, struggled to keep concentration all the way to the end/ became more aware of the surroundings again rather than just me and the music
5 - really satisfying bit of music, just following along with the melodic line and the dynamics, before 'coming back into the room' again and realising it was near the end of the excerpt and getting ready to end
Comments: Played this piece many years ago as an audition piece when I was in school, but it has fond memories rather than tense ones as it is so lovely to play - and really satisfying when it goes well. The melodic lines are really easy on the ear and although there are challenging aspects, they don't stick out so much as to take you away from enjoying playing. Today's performance was a bit more shaky and so thoughts about that often interrupted the 'flow', but that's always going to happen to some extent in live performances.
ReadMusic: yes and no

Measure numbers: The whole head (melody), two choruses, and a head out.
Observations: A lot of the moments when i felt absorbed in the music was moments in improvisation where i felt i had found a way of navigating the chord changes and had a fluid idea to expand on. Due to the nature of improvisation, where you always have to be calculating the harmony and possible directions to go, it can be difficult to be flow freely, and being 'in the zone' isn't always a common occurence, but moments where the ideas work tend to aid in being completely absorbed/immersed in the music.
Comments: certain factors which contributed to me being less absorbed in the music where, the performance space. For example, i respond better to a larger audience and tend to be more focused and perform to a higher standard than in informal spaces where there is less to respond to in the room. Also playing with a backing track instead of a live band is more limiting due to a lack of response.
ReadMusic: Yes, but most of it is lead sheet music where the melody is more of a guidance to be embellished. For performances i learn the music off by heart, but chord changes can be more difficult to memorise.

Piece: Suite III in C for cello solo BWV 1009: Gigue
Observations: Head movements seem to be more pronounced here, as well as mouth tension and maybe eyelids slightly more shut. I decided based on my memory mainly, not scrutinising the recording, but maybe one would be able to tell. Having chosen to play music with repeats (AABB), it seems I concentrated more on playing the second time better and was more free the first time around in general. I had no bowing or fingering markings prepared and was sight-reading to a small extent, so I was freest in the runs of easier notes with less rhythmic complexity or awkward fingering to worry about, I think.
Comments: My facial expression is relaxed before and after playing, but shows a remarkably quick descent into concentration and vice versa.
PerformanceFrequency: During university, around 6 engagements a year as a soloist or chamber musician plus around 16 concerts a year in larger ensembles; also recording very casual Instagram content around once a month
ReadMusic: I am a stronger sight-reader and weaker memoriser; I only memorise classical music when encouraged to for assessment purposes, and struggle with popular music which isn't notated. I have a habit of not annotating as much as I should, so I do memorise *how* to play the notated music.

Observations:
The first two sections noted are equivalent.
Generally, when the music was easier with respect to technique, I became absorbed in the music.
Paired notes eg. m. 23 make me particularly absorbed in the music.
Most of the time, when absorbed in the music, I am just listening to the changing harmonies and the tension and release.
Comments: Listening back, I was absorbed in the same places, although I found it harder to become absorbed when listening as I was more aware of tiny inaccuracies.
ReadMusic: Yes, I read music. If playing a solo recital, I will generally play from memory. If I am just playing for fun or practicing, I will use music but aim to play by heart at the end of learning a piece.
